	<div class="post" id="post-2">
		<div class="title">
    		<h2>Journal</h2>
		</div>
		<div class="entry">
			<table id="table43" style="table-layout: fixed; height: 2806px;" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
<tbody>
<tr>
<td class="textTimeHeader" height="20" valign="top">SUNDAY, FEBRUARY 01, 2009 12:40 AM, CST</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textNormal12">
<div style="overflow: auto;">I really could use everyone&#8217;s help. </p>
<p>As of January 26th, 2009 Amy and I decided to leave MD Anderson. None of the treatments used seemed to work as we had hoped and my lymphoma had been growing back as furiously and aggressive as in the very beginning. I felt like I had lost my momentum to my cure by going to MD Anderson at all. It is a machine of an institution, I felt like a number, and that my case wasn&#8217;t important enough to really seek options outside of the box. My Oncologist seemed to work just hard enough in order to avoid Amy and I speaking to patient advocacy. </p>
<p>One Sunday even as my lymphoma was growing by the day I knew I was waiting for my counts to regain in order to try yet another type of treatment. It was called R-Gemox. This was normally used for different types of &#8216;C&#8217; words, but somehow was thrown out as a possible options with new drugs to try that my body may not be so resistant to. I woke up to a little bit of excretion happening from my site and was extremely nervous. I called the hospital all day starting at 11am (5 times total) in order to let the on call doctor know so I could determine whether to go in to ER or not. Not until 9pm did I finally receive a call back from my doctor&#8217;s nurse. That was only because we had to get an Admin involved. She told me that we did not need an infection and that I may need to admit myself into the ER and have cultures done. We thought this was the best plan so we went in that next day hoping to start treatment a little early.</p>
<p>I sat in the ER for hours while they contacted the Lymphoma doctor on call. My doctor was conveniently on vacation yet AGAIN as it was Martin Luther King&#8217;s birthday and a holiday for all outpatient clinics. I have never experienced a facility that takes so much time off. I was finally sent up the Lymphoma floor and admitted into a room. Amy and I waited, and waited, and waited thinking I would start treatment immediately because my blood counts were in perfect standing. That was a mistake because due to the fact we cried possible infection the treatment could not start until the cultures came back negative. It was smart but discerning for me considering that this tumor was not getting any smaller. </p>
<p>As of Wednesday that same week I finally got started with my treatment. I was genuinely excited but started to experience some swelling of my throat. I could breath through my nose fine but woke up in a panic as I found myself with a constant flem catch in my air passage. It wasn&#8217;t a snore but a gurgle. I was pacing in the room about every two hours not sure what to make of it. I have never been this nervous for my life this whole time. Amy woke up and tried to comfort me but did not realize the magnitude of the situation. I decided to breath through and calm myself down so I could sleep. It was a true test that I was not even sure I could conquer.</p>
<p>The next morning I couldn&#8217;t swallow even a cup of water. It literally came back up as I thought I might choke. I couldn&#8217;t eat either and was freaking out. I tried to tell the nurse on staff but she just kept asking me the dumbest questions as if it was not registering what was wrong. I could barely talk. As if that was not an indication. The worst moment was when I finished my chemotherapy there were about five Oncologist that came into my room and were staring blank at me(this is a common thing there). One was even a chairman of the lymphoma department. He said he was ready to doscharge me as I finished my treatment that morning. I looked at him like he was crazy. I said, I can barely talk right, my throat is completely swollen, I cannot drink or eat. Why the hell would he send me home?? He did not see it as a problem so I had to make it a problem. He decided to get an ENT involved to inspect my throat. </p>
<p>The ENT specialists put a scope through my nose which was a strange feeling and ordered a CT Scan of my head only. Apparently adema had been building up around my throat because my lymph nodes were clogged and unable to pass any fluid through. They put me on a high dose steroid that night via IV drip. I woke up feeling like a million bucks but was not out of the fire just yet because my neck was still heavily swollen. Although I could eat, drink, and talk so that was a step in the right direction. </p>
<p>I was finally discharged and given an oral steroid to keep reducing the swelling. I was happy to be home but my tumor was not shrinking by any means from treatment. I was so discouraged but felt there has to be something else we can try. I mean really the goal is to at least get my lymphoma under control enough to throw me in to my stem cell transplant. I have had amazing response to chemotherapy before so what was going wrong? Everything since we left Pensacola just felt wrong. From the treatment, to the neglect, to the scheduling,..something just wasn&#8217;t right. This is a state of the art facility and world renowned for its progressive nature. Why was I slipping through the cracks? Why did I feel unimportant in my case?</p>
<p>That following Monday we met with my Oncologist. It was a meeting that gave Amy and I our answer but that was not such a good thing. She basically told me I was running out of options and if we felt home would be a better place to be then she understood. I couldn&#8217;t believe it,&#8230;she basically said, &#8216;I give up.&#8217; She did the whole rub on the back, sympathy at a distance. Amy had these print outs of other possible drugs and clinical trials and wanted to hand them to the doctor simply to acknowledge the possibility. She would not even take them from Amy&#8217;s hand to read through. This was so disrespectful. Dr Sunnenberg in Pensacola always encouraged our proactive nature and really worked hard to find us answers. Of course that&#8217;s when I was so close to remission too. At that point Amy looked her dead in her eye and said,&#8217;We thank you for your honesty.&#8217; She did not know how respond but still nodded her head as if she got what Amy meant by that. </p>
<p>We left feeling more lost than ever. We had a decision to make and MD Anderson was leaving us any choice. We knew for a fact home in Pensacola we had an amazing man that truly had an invested interest in my cure. We also had a few friends that were constantly searching for answers. Bijan and our friend Robbie are just the most amazing people. Both Burkitt&#8217;s survivors and ready to fight with me still. Robbie had been talking our Oncologist at Emory University Winship Cancer Institute in Atlanta keeping him posted on my situation. While in the meantime Bijan was searching for clinical trials to help find ew drugs on the market I could try. Amy and I were on the phone for two days straight. If MD Anderson would not prove themselves then we knew another facility would. Dr Flowers at Emory called and gae us a sense of peace. He had ideas that nobody else were presenting to us and was ready to bring me in and try. He also knew he could coordinate them with Dr Sunnenberg in Pensacola so we knew home was the place we needed to be. It just felt right.</p>
<p>In an instant, Amy and I packed up and left our dear friends Brent and Leslie. It was so abrupt and uncertain but just felt necessary considering that Monday morning meeting. I called Jill at MD Anderson, one of the APN&#8217;s and told her we had to go. She was very helpful in how we could obtain my records and images to bring back. We were also set up for our first meeting with Dr Hosing(my stem cell transplant doctor). The day we were going to leave neck just did not look good as if it were swelling yet again. There was so much to do at MD Anderson but time was against us so we just left. </p>
<p>On the way home I got a phone call from another one of my Oncologist&#8217;s nurses about us leaving. I told her that I apologize for the immediate action and that we appreciated my doctor&#8217;s help but knew we could get more options back in Pensacola. I kid you not when that conversation shifted everything. Not twenty minutes later I got a call from my doctor at MD Anderson. I apologized again, but explained our meeting Monday gave Amy and I the answer we needed to leave and seek treatment somewhere else. I was disappointed in having to make such a rash decision but it obviously changed the dynamic completely of my situation. My doctor said she had been searching clinical trials for me!!! I was shocked. She said she found some and was emailing the doctors conducting them for me and would inform Dr Sunnenberg as soon as she heard back. Amy and I both cried. Things were finally coming together from MD Anderson. All because we left. I cannot determine if her colleagues put some pressure on her, or if her hands were not tied to them any longer due to our decision. All I know is she finally was stepping outside of the box and the machine that is MD Anderson. We drove home faster than we  could ever imagine just to get back to Pensacola so Dr Sunnenberg could see what was going on. We literally just showed up on his doorstep. </p>
<p>I wanted to kiss the ground regardless of how bad things have gotten. There is just something about home that I just missed. Rightfully so. Shit went all wrong out at MD Anderson. There were just too many hands in the pot and protocols that nobody was willing to budge on for my LIFE. As usual, even in th darkest moment Dr Sunnenberg was not even phased. He was ready to see my cure through once again even if that meant calling Dr Flowers and Dr Fanale out at MD Anderson to coordinate something else to try. Amy and I went back to our piece of heaven at home and felt empowered again. It&#8217;s just that sense of peace when you are with a doctor that is open minded and willing to fight just as hard as you are. </p>
<p>I was a little nervous about swelling though and my steroids were a taper so that meant I would take less and less each day. Apparently, that was not effective. Sure enough I woke up at 4am close to no being able to swallow or eat again. I was in pain from the tumor spreading around my temple, jaw, and neck and did not want to let this thing get out of hand again. So, as opposed to a 35 mile drive we simply got into our car and drove,&#8230;oh, 2 minutes down the road to the ER. I was admitted into our local hospital and started on steroids immediately.</p>
<p>I am in my room and get a call from Peter, Dr Fanale&#8217;s direct APN. He was spouting off about this clinical trial they found for me at MD Anderson!!! I was thrown off, scared, unsure, but was also being told I needed to go in for couple tests to get started. It was our answer!! I emailed Dr Sunnenberg, got a call from one of the nurses involved in the trial to get more details about the drugs used and requirements, and in a matter of like 6 hours I was making plans to drive BACK to MD Anderson of all places! Among Dr Flowers, Dr Sunnenberg, and Dr Fanale, all agreed this was a smart thing to do. I thought to myself, the intention was to be cured at MD Anderson so I guess that is where we need to be again.</p>
<p>Amy and I were and still are ecstatic. On top of it all my beautiful family surprised me by coming down to Pensacola. My mom, sister, and dad just got on the road and left to be with us! This has to be the answer. It just does. Amy and I have endured so uch over this year and we are so close to my cure. I know things seem to get really intense with me(it&#8217;s always just been that way) but they always work out for the best. As of right now, we are driving out to Houston early Sunday morning, I have a couple tests Monday, and if all is well then I go int this trial already by Wednesday!</p>
<p>This is where I am asking all of the amazing support from you as you have been so great before and in this case I really need the focus solely to go along these lines:</p>
<p>1. My heart function must be above 48%<br />2. This treatment HAS to put in me into remission and get me into my stem cell transplant&#8230;it must be this way<br />3. And my stem cell transplant needs to happen ASAP</p>
<p>Please keep me in your prayers this week and try to focus on the fact this WILL work. I know I am manifesting this and have asked Amy and our family to leave all doubt aside and believe in this being my cure. I want to tell you all that I love you dearly&#8230; friends, strangers, etc. Your comments and guest book entries have carried us so far and this is where we find success in my journey. Have a beautiful weekend and I will keep you posted with total updates of success.</p>
<p>To Robbie, Bijan, Cheryl, Kevin, and Kyler&#8230;this is it! Thank you so much for your search, your support, and giving me so much hope as you have from surviving. We found my cure.</p>
<p>Love,<br />Christopher &#038; Amy</p>
</div>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td height="25">
<hr size="1" /></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textTimeHeader" height="20" valign="top">FRIDAY, JANUARY 16, 2009 08:14 AM, CST</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textNormal12">
<div style="overflow: auto;">I am sitting at MD Anderson&#8230;waiting as usual.   It seems that is all we do these days is wait and wait.  Chris is going to start a new chemo in the next few days&#8230;everything is contingent on his counts.  It is called GEM-P with Rituxin.  This particular chemo is specific to refractory lymphomas&#8230;both hodgkins and non hodgkins.  He will be admitted for 3 days.  We thought this would possibly be an out patient regime but just found out yesterday that he will be in the hospital for this one.  It&#8217;s only three days which is nothing for Chris.  He even said yesterday&#8230;that this would be a piece of cake.   He has a team of lymphoma specialist that are working for him.  they are all discussing his case&#8230;presenting it to different boards and gathering info like crazy.  We really trust his care team.<br />
Chris is doing well. He had  a rash all over his head and arms and a little on his chest.  It was infected hair follicles.  He said it was uncomfortable the first few days but has cleared up nicely.  He has been on steroids the last few days to help with swelling.  He takes about 10 a day and can effect his patience level and his overall mood.  these are all minor things to him though.  His attitude is still amazing and we are keeping our eye on the prize&#8230;which is stem cell transplant.<br />
He has cord blood ( from infants) ready for him but the problem with cord blood is that it doesn&#8217;t have as much Graph versus Tumor effect because it is such a new immune system.   The Cord Blood is powerful stuff and has worked well for leukemia and aids&#8230;so it is still a great option They are still searching for adult blood in the system everyday and he has over 100 potential matches.<br />
So much has happened since I last updated.  And I apologize for not keeping you all informed.  I have decided to not update as much and touch on the most important factors in our journey.  I feel it&#8217;s important for others who search the internet for answers to learn from Chris and from our journey.<br />
We love living with Brent and Leslie.  We live a full life here in Houston and stay busy most of the time.  We miss our friends&#8230;.  Who we do not get to see often at all, due to travel and being here in TX.</p>
<p>So that is all for now.  I will keep you all posted about this new chemo treatment.</p>
<p>Love,<br />
Amy</p></div>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td height="25">
<hr size="1" /></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textTimeHeader" height="20" valign="top">THURSDAY, JANUARY 01, 2009 07:21 PM, CST</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textNormal12">
<div style="overflow: auto;">Okay, so I tried to actually update MY own journal for once and after numerous &#8216;continued session&#8217; attempts ultimately I made the mistake of not copying what I wrote before I tried to save the information. No update was made and it had kicked me out of the administrative section before it was too late and everything I wrote was lost. I know this is a big shock for me to update the journal for once but I wanted to give Amy a break. It seems each day is such a rush of emotions and recording it can have its drawbacks of reliving those struggles(if any).</p>
<p>Amy went home to Pensacola after my first treatment here at MD Anderson so she could see our friends and work. She was very reluctant to leave me but knew it was necessary to get back to a semi normal life if even for a short period of time.</p>
<p>She got a chance to talk to some amazing friends that gave her the best support as well as have a little fun in the process. I do not want to give a false impression of our life. I know friends and family see our Facebook/MySpace pages and think every day is a holiday for us, but they do not see the daily frustrations in the rollercoaster involved with my treatment. Aside from that I refuse to apologize for trying to live a normal life through all of this. Therefore, we put on our best smiles and look positively to the future by making plans and enjoying all there is to life within the confines of my limitations. I will only state this once to make a brief point. I try my hardest to keep my family and friends in the loop but if I do not call or write 24/7 it&#8217;s nothing personal. I am always pushing to keep the bills paid by working full time as well as keep all of my appointments for treatment. For everyone to simply write a few words or make one phone call is way less effort than Amy or I making 20 phone calls or writing 20 emails. That is why these blogs are so incredible. It helps us maintain a balance while keeping our loved ones informed. Okay, I am off my soapbox.</p>
<p>Recently, I have had a few challenges but things seem to be progressing in the right direction. Being in a highly credited institution does not necessarily mean efficiency. The care here at MD Anderson is amazing but I still give Pensacola&#8217;s Sacred Heart a lot of credit for its personal attention. Some hurdles I have experienced is nobody wants to make a decision without your physician so when your physician is on vacation then you suffer. Burkitts Lymphoma does not give you holidays off. I know I could go to see my amazing Oncologist Dr. Sunnenberg and things happen fast when necessary. I would also see him more frequently giving intimate knowledge of my progression and setbacks. That is just not the case here. I felt the same way with Emory Winship Cancer Institute. We are strapped to making this work as they are the Stem Cell transplant pros.</p>
<p>Amy and Liz drove here to be with me Christmas. My parents and Amy&#8217;s dad also made it to be with me. I was so happy to be with my immediate family. I am staying in Conroe TX for the time being and my friends Brent and Leslie have gone beyond what one could hope to make me feel welcome in their home and apart of their family. They made it possible for this Christmas to be the best one yet. We all got wonderful gifts, went to some awesome dinners and just relaxed together at the house. We saw a couple movies, got some laughs in and continued to enjoy every minute as we always do. That is no change of pace either so when we hear the phrase &#8216;Enjoy every minute during this time together&#8217;&#8230;not to sound cocky but we already did because we are madly in love with each other.</p>
<p>Oh!!! The benefit my friends had in Alexandria VA for me was amazing!!! I got to video conference in and see friends I have not seen for years as well as new beautiful people that helped to put the event together. The event raised over $8,000.00 from donated art, t-shirts, woodallions(bling bing chains made of WOOD), stickers, etc. It was a mixed crowd there to support me whether they knew me personally or not. I was in awe and I am so appreciative. This gives Amy and I flexibility financially to pay these new bills, fly Amy back to Pensacola to work occasionally, and to keep available for new expenses that come up throughout my treatment.</p>
<p>I can safely say we have still hit some hurdles, but continue to have such high hopes for the inevitable cure. We have had to fight a little but overall we take the amazing support and move one step forward. Dr. Sunnenberg, Amy, and the love from friends/family is my cure ultimately. Chemicals can only do so much physically while these amazing people have worked their butt off to see me into remission. I am right there. Give me one or two more treatments and transplant here we come!!!</p>
<p>I love you all so much.</p>
<p>Love,<br />
Christopher</p></div>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td height="25">
<hr size="1" /></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textTimeHeader" height="20" valign="top">THURSDAY, DECEMBER 11, 2008 10:05 AM, CST</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textNormal12">
<div style="overflow: auto;">Chris is being discharged today! yea!  We are ready to be home!  We are waiting to speak to the he doctors.  All of his tests came back CLEAR. We got the final ones yesterday so we are super excited about that.  He scored a 95% on his pulminary test yesterday&#8230;which is outstanding after what he has been through!!!!! I swear you guys&#8230;my husband is a BEAST&#8230;he just takes all the stuff they do to him and he keeps going and going.  Never complains&#8230;never will say he is tired.   He is so strong.  I see the strength in him everyday.  And I reassure him that &#8216;it&#8217;s okay to be tired&#8230;or feel like crap&#8217;.  He&#8217;s entitled!!!!  But he never will say it&#8230;not unless I ask!<br />
I have a million questions to ask the docs today&#8230;I am sitting on my bed in a pile of papers &#8230;everything from all his blood work to all of the Stem Cell documents to his appointment schedules.  I am trying to sort it out and comprise all my questions before we go today.<br />
well..that&#8217;s all for now.  Houston will be our home for awhile&#8230;Chris is in the BEST hands!  I have no worries&#8230;and that is saying a lot for me!  I usually question everybody!!!  I&#8217;ll still have my list of concerns&#8230;but most of the time they are on top of things!  I am so grateful he is here.</p>
<p>We want to thank our friends and family for  hinking of us&#8230;.calling, sending messages and e-mails.  It means so much to us!  We love you guys!</p>
<p>Amy</p></div>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td height="25">
<hr size="1" /></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textTimeHeader" height="20" valign="top">WEDNESDAY, DECEMBER 10, 2008 07:07 PM, CST</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textNormal12">
<div style="overflow: auto;">Wow&#8230;.24 hours can make a huge difference!!!!!  So the Big.lymphoma Guy&#8230;Dr. Fayad advised us to stay here in Houston..  He said it is very crucial that we not miss an opportunity to cure chris and if there is travel involved then&#8230;we could miss that opportunity and it could be fatal.  That&#8217;s all we needed to hear&#8230;we are staying right here in Houston!!!!!  So, our Friends and family are coming to stay here with us at Brent and Leslie&#8217;s and it will be a great christmas&#8230;no matter what!</p>
<p>I feel really good about Chris staying here.  I feel like he is in good hands!  All his tests came back clean!  Yea!  The chemo is working well so far&#8230;we have started the Stem Cell Transplant process&#8230;we are on our way!!!!  I will commute back and forth and be with him as much as possible.  Leslie ( the friend we are staying with) said she would cook for Chris and look after him &#8230;and be my &#8220;stand in&#8221;:) while I am gone.  I trust that he is going to be taken care.  Brent and Leslie and amazing people with big hearts and we feel so blessed to have them in our life.</p>
<p>So&#8230;Chris will be discharged tomorrow.  He will have home health care come in this weekend to give him I.V. fluids.  This flushes the chemo through his kidneys and bladder.  I will leave to go home on Sunday and come back to Houston on the 22nd to be with him.  One day at a time&#8230;that&#8217;s all we can think about.</p>
<p>All in all, Chris is doing well.  He is tired from the chemo&#8230;his fatique level is high&#8230;but that is to be expected.  Other than that&#8230;he has had very little nausia&#8230;his appetite is great and he looks really good.  You would never knowhe&#8217;s been through so much.   I have to say I feel confidant about this process&#8230;I am trusting that all the pieces will come together at the PERFECT time.</p>
<p>Love, Amy</p></div>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td height="25">
<hr size="1" /></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textTimeHeader" height="20" valign="top">TUESDAY, DECEMBER 09, 2008 09:41 AM, CST</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textNormal12">
<div style="overflow: auto;">The time has flown by&#8230;one day is running into the next and I couldn&#8217;t tell you what the date is.  When your in the hospital&#8230;time is so different.<br />
Today&#8230;Chris has his final test.  His MRI is scheduled for 1:30 pm.  It&#8217;s of the brain.  Then, hopefully we will receive some results of the LP and bone marrow biopsy.  After we get these done and get the results&#8230;we will be able to breathe a sigh of relief!<br />
We are so happy with the chemo results.  The chemo has been &#8216;not as bad&#8217; as the Hyper-Cvad but more consistent.  It&#8217;s interesting.  I can tell that Chris doesn&#8217;t feel as run down&#8230;he is tired for sure but it hasn&#8217;t knocked him completely out.  of coarse we have 3 more days to go&#8230;so we will see what happens.<br />
He did not get sick for the intrathecal methotrexate.  This was the procedure that made him have rigors and vomiting.  But this time he did wonderful!!!<br />
The nurses were amazed this morning when they saw Chris.   The results are astonishing!  We are praying for perfect timing.  We are praying that chemo starts at the perfect time and Stem cell starts at the perfect time.  We don&#8217;t want there to be any time for growth.<br />
I plan to speak with the Stem cell team before we leave.  I want to get the ball rolling and find out what we need to do about swabbing kits for family and getting the proper approvals done.  It&#8217;s a HUGE process.</p>
<p>We plan to stay in Houston after Chris is discharged for a couple days to let him start to feel somewhat normal.  Then we plan to head home on Sunday.  I will have to give Chris shots of nuepogen everyday to raise his WBCs ( white blood counts).  This will help his blood recover so that he can have his chemo right on schedule.</p>
<p>Well, that&#8217;s all for now. He is doing well.  His spirits are up thanks to all of you!!!!!  keep the guest book signings coming, phone calls and e-mails.  This is the best medicine for Chris&#8230;he loves to feel connected to all of you.  It&#8217;s easy to feel isolated in this place.</p>
<p>Thanks for All your support!</p>
<p>Love,</p>
<p>Amy</p>
<p>I want to thank my work&#8230;especially Sheri for rescheduling all my clients for me&#8230;and for my clients being so understanding.  It allows me to be totally &#8216;present&#8217; for Chris and to give him All my attention.  Thank you so much!!!:)</p></div>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td height="25">
<hr size="1" /></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textTimeHeader" height="20" valign="top">MONDAY, DECEMBER 08, 2008 02:16 PM, CST</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textNormal12">
<div style="overflow: auto;">Well&#8230;the chemo started yesterday.  So far so good. A little nausea this morning but no vomiting.  I can see the look in his eye&#8230;that his worn out and sick of being in bed.  The Doc came in this morning and said he is doing good. He had his lumbar puncture today.  It was pretty uncomfortable for him.  He had to breathe through it&#8230;and he broke out in a sweat from head to toe.  His heart rate is a little high because of the stress.  He has had 5 of these lumbar punctures and they are no fun.  They are not painful but uncomfortable and the anticipation is the worst part.  They tried to do one on him on Friday&#8230;with out X-ray and had him hunched over a table in the hospital room poking and prodding around his spine for quite sometime.  Needless to say they were not able to achieve anything and Chris was very stressed out&#8230;his blood pressure was high&#8230;.it really sucks.  If they had read his records they would have seen that the previous LP&#8217;s were preformed with Floroscopy.  This lack of communication is what really urks me&#8230;it&#8217;s unnecessary pain&#8230;discomfort&#8230;not to mention premeds they pumped into his body for No reason at all.  All because they never reviewed his previous LP record.<br />
The one thing that I have learned is to ask AS MANY questions about everything I can.  I am constantly challenging the doctors and nurses to make sure they are on their toes.  I&#8217;m sure I&#8217;m annoying to them&#8230;but I don&#8217;t care.  My WHOLE focus is Chris&#8230;I don&#8217;t care if they have to triple check themselves&#8230;I want it done right!  I repeat myself over and over again.  If we didn&#8217;t mention a lot of his past experience he would have had so many mishaps.  It is really scary.  But the lesson in all of this&#8230;is that only you or someone close to you is your BEST advocate.  Do not rely on the doctors.<br />
I&#8217;m feeling home sick today.  It&#8217;s only Monday&#8230;we have a long way to go. But hopefully this treatment will shrink the tumor and it will all be worth it&#8230;every bit!</p>
<p>Love,<br />
Amy</p></div>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td height="25">
