<td height="25">
<hr size="1" /></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textTimeHeader" height="20" valign="top">SUNDAY, DECEMBER 06, 2008 04:48 PM, CST</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textNormal12">
<div style="overflow: auto;">Great news!  We were transferred to the lymphoma floor&#8230;AND Chris is starting chemo right now!!!!  YEA!  His blood work looked great&#8230;his PET scan and CT scan looked clear!  Fingers are crossed!!!!!  The difference is night and day from the floor we were on to this floor.  The people here are so sweet and so helpful and they know EXACTLY what Chris is going through.  The other floor specialized in nuerological type cancer and rehabilitation.  They did not understand how aggressive Burkitt&#8217;s lymphoma is.</p>
<p>Our room is great!  VERY spacious and my little bed is comfy&#8230;great view too!  I told Chris we should just try to pretend we are on vacation at the Beau Rivage or something.  So&#8230;we are acting as if we are enjoying some down time and a mini vacation!!!!  You have to fake it till you make it sometimes!</p>
<p>The benefit went great lastnight!!!!  Chris was so excited to see everyone!  It lifted his spirits so much and made him feel super cared about and loved.  He used his webcam&#8230;it was really awesome that he could be apart of it&#8230;so many miles away:)!  Tonight is the second night of the benefit.  Chris will &#8220;webcam in&#8221; tonight as well.</p>
<p>Chris is recieving his premeds right now and is feeling very sleepy.  The benedryl is a kicker&#8230;it knocks him out for about 45 minutes.  And then his first bag of chemo will be hung in just a few minutes!  We are so happy to get started!  Chris and I also found out that he will be able to walk around the WHOLE entire MD Anderson hospital!  This is so awesome because usually he is confined to his room and it feels somewhat like prison.  So it&#8217;s a super big treat to be able to walk around with Chris and go to the aquariam&#8230;listen to the band in the lobby&#8230;look outside.  We are considering the possibility of coming back here for the rest of his chemo.  They seem much more efficient here on the lymphoma floor and the care superceeds pensacola for sure!!!  We were really scared for the first three days&#8230;we thought this place was a nightmare!  But after we talked to the administrator ( thanks to Ndu) and to the oncologist this morning&#8230;things have changed for the better and our confidence is officially restored in MD Anderson!:)</p>
<p>Love,</p>
<p>Amy</p></div>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td height="25">
<hr size="1" /></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textTimeHeader" height="20" valign="top">FRIDAY, DECEMBER 05, 2008 02:32 PM, CST</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textNormal12">
<div style="overflow: auto;">Well&#8230;.MD Anderson has been interesting!  Can&#8217;t say we are totally impressed.  We had a mishap in the beginning of our visit which spiraled into a domino effect.  Needless to say our first day was extremely disappointing!  There seems to be an EXTREME communication gap here.  It&#8217;s as if the nurses and doctors do not talk to each other nor do they read the notes.  We literally have nurses ask US what the plan is for the day.  Can you imagine being admitted into the hospital and the nurses ask YOU what the plan is for your treatment!!!!!  Wow!<br />
Anyway&#8230;..we are giving them the benefit of the doubt and hoping that things change in a more positive direction.  We met a very nice nurse named &#8216;Ndu&#8217;.  he paged the doctor and one phone call made all the difference.  Ndu said&#8217; communication is one of the biggest parts of nursing and when we as nurses forget this component&#8230;we have failed our patients miserably&#8217;.  He apologized for the anxiety we felt around not knowing what was going on.  He was very nice and so helpful!  Thank you Ndu!!!!!!!!</p>
<p>Dr. Fanale expressed concern about Chris not responding totally to previous treatment.  she said there are no clinical trials for Burkitt&#8217;s due to it&#8217;s rare nature.  BUT&#8230;she did say that they have not done a head to head study on R-HYPER/CVAD versus R-MCODOX/IVAC  and there is great success with this later treatment.  Chris has to have a 50% shrinkage in tumor size to qualify for a stem cell transplant.  We will speak to the stem cell team and decide on who to send swabbing kits to for donor possibilities.  If there is a good response to treatment and remission then&#8230;they will most likely do a auto stem cell transplant.</p>
<p>So far Chris has had a chest x-ray, ct scan, pet scan, and bone marrow biopsy on both hips.  he is waiting for his intrathecal methotrexate and lumbar puncture procedure.  He is on-call for an MRI tonight.  He WILL start chemo tomorrow morning!!!  Yea!  We ask that you all pray for a good response!!!  We want to watch this thing melt away before our eyes again.</p>
<p>The benefit for Chris is tonight in V.A.  We are so excited because Chris is going to hopefully webcam into the party so that he can video conference with friends while in the hospital&#8230;I love modern technology!!!</p>
<p>Thank you for all of your support!  we appreciate all of you and your friendship and unconditional love!</p>
<p>We received the results of the CT scan and so far everything is coming back CLEAR of disease!!!  We will keep you all posted on the results as they come in.</p>
<p>Love you guys&#8230;wish we could be there at the benefit!  You have No idea what this means to us.  To all the people who are behind this &#8230;thank you from the bottom of our heart!  You know who you are!</p>
<p>Here&#8217;s to Chris and his CURE!!!!</p>
<p>Amy</p></div>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td height="25">
<hr size="1" /></td>
