<tr>
<td class="textTimeHeader" height="20" valign="top">SATURDAY, NOVEMBER 29, 2008 07:59 AM, CST</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textNormal12">
<div style="overflow: auto;">Well the lump is there but not growing thanks to the chemo.  It shrunk a little the first day but then that&#8217;s all.  Chris has appointments ALL week at MD Anderson.  He just got his schedule last night and he has something going on pretty much everyday.  Mostly meetings and testing at this point.  No treatment yet.  We are not sure if he will receive the first rounds of chemo here or if they want to treat him there.  Chris would prefer to be treated at home but we&#8217;ll see.  Dr. Sunnenberg said that this chemo for Chris will be a breeze!  He&#8217;s already had the horrible stuff and this isn&#8217;t anything like that.  That&#8217;s reassuring and good to know.  He said methotrexate is the worst you can get and he has already had three 24 hour bags of that stuff&#8230;YUCK!<br />
Hopefully Chris will breeze through the prep chemo for the transplant.<br />
We are excited to meet Brent and Leslie.  They are the ones who are taking us in to their home for the time that we are in Houston.  They have set up an office for Chris so that he can work.  Their place sounds amazing!<br />
We should get to Houston the evening of Tuesday, December 2nd.<br />
Chris is going to get his chemo this morning. His last bag is today.  We are a little anxious about that.  Not sure if it will start to grow or not.   I would think they would do something about it in Houston if it becomes an issue.</p>
<p>Hope all of you had a wonderful Thanksgiving!!!</p>
<p>Love,<br />
Amy</p></div>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td height="25">
<hr size="1" /></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textTimeHeader" height="20" valign="top">WEDNESDAY, NOVEMBER 26, 2008 05:37 PM, CST</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textNormal12">
<div style="overflow: auto;">Chris and I  were at the doctors office for about 3 hours this morning.  We have realized&#8230;nothing is simple and quick&#8230;.except radiation.  Hopefully that theory will change soon!<br />
Well, he received vincristine and a new drug.  Pretty strong  stuff&#8230;I would tell you the name but I&#8217;m too lazy to get up and search in my file for it. It&#8217;s one of the &#8216;mycin&#8217;s&#8217;  Bleomycin??????  Something like that.  Anyway..It&#8217;s working!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!  The tumor is shrinking once more.  This thing really plays with our emotions.</p>
<p>He is wearing his  portable pump&#8230;SO COOL!  Sure beats the hospital or even sitting in the infusion center.  The doctors theory is that saturating the cell consistently is better then giving it to you in one shot.  They are still testing this theory but makes sense to me because this way it never gives the cells time to divide.</p>
<p>This whole chemo thing is such a science and although it&#8217;s quite scary&#8230;it&#8217;s very interesting.  I learned that vincristine is derived from several plants.  One is called the &#8216;Happy Tree&#8217;&#8230;well I guess it&#8217;s all in how you look at it!:)  If it works&#8230;we&#8217;re &#8216;happy&#8217;!!!!</p>
<p>We decided to stay home instead of going out to Portofino.  Chris has to have his bag changed every morning and our little dog is going to be in the &#8216;pet resort&#8217; ( so cute) for awhile &#8230;so it doesn&#8217;t make sense to stay out on the beach right now.  Maybe when we get home!  This is my first Thanksgiving since my mom passed away last December from breast cancer&#8230;WOW&#8230;it&#8217;s a crazy time of year for us.  We miss her.  So&#8230;I&#8217;m cooking (yikes).  It will be a beautiful day&#8230;and she will be with us in spirit.   A very interesting thing happened to me&#8230;.I had a lady&#8230;a complete stranger hug me in the middle of Target yesterday.  She said she would love to give me a hug, if I needed one.  Now&#8230;this type of thing obviously doesn&#8217;t happen everyday.  She was the sweetest woman&#8230;very sincere and Something about her reminded me of my mother.  Maybe it was&#8230;in a crazy kind of way.  Nothing surprises me anymore!:)</p>
<p>Well, that&#8217;s all for now&#8230;..Happy Thanksgiving everyone!</p>
<p>We are thankful for:<br />
Our marriage and unconditional love for each other<br />
Our family&#8230;we miss you!<br />
All of our wonderful friends<br />
Chris&#8217; tumor going down<br />
The amazing fund raisers you all have done for Chris<br />
That Chris isn&#8217;t in the hospital<br />
For Chris&#8217; amazing company NSS<br />
For our insurance issues working out<br />
For Robbie<br />
For Jill, Brent and Leslie&#8230;.Thank you for our home away from home&#8230;<br />
For being able to go to MD Anderson.<br />
For all the strangers who have shown us support and love.</p>
<p>We are so blessed! Our gratitude list goes on and on!</p>
<p>We love you!</p>
<p>Amy</p></div>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td height="25">
<hr size="1" /></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textTimeHeader" height="20" valign="top">TUESDAY, NOVEMBER 25, 2008 05:26 PM, CST</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textNormal12">
<div style="overflow: auto;">We found out today that Starting tomorrow morning at 8 am&#8230;.Chris will be hooked up to a 24 hour chemo pump that he will wear on his body for the next 4 days.  The pump looks something like a &#8216;fanny pack&#8217;. The drug he will receive will be a chemo drug called Vincristine. It kills rapidly dividing cells.<br />
This means we will not be in the hospital!!!  Yeah!  Chris will go everyday at 8am to get his bag of chemo changed.<br />
Dr. Romagueara @ MD Anderson recommended we do this to get us through until his first round of salvage chemo. (Which is what he will do prior to the Stem Cell Transplant.)<br />
We will be hopefully spending our Thankgiving out at Portofino Resort.  This was a sweet gift from a client of mine.</p>
<p>We are looking for ward to M.D Anderson&#8230;so that Chris doesn&#8217;t feel like a genie pig anymore.  Enough is enough!</p>
<p>Amy</p></div>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td height="25">
<hr size="1" /></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textTimeHeader" height="20" valign="top">MONDAY, NOVEMBER 24, 2008 03:53 PM, CST</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textNormal12">
<div style="overflow: auto;">We saw Dr. Sunnenberg today. It&#8217;s confirmed&#8230;the lump is coming back.  He said he is going to contact Chris&#8217; Doctor in Houston to decide which chemo he will be receiving to buy more time before Chris&#8217; appointment on December 3rd @ MD Anderson.  We don&#8217;t know if it will be outpatient or inpatient chemo&#8230;so we may be spending thanksgiving in the hospital.  If Chris has out patient chemo then we will stay at Portofino  Resort&#8230;where we were married and enjoy a Thanksgiving dinner at Terracotta&#8230;a restaurant and place that is dear to our hearts! But we just want to do what is right&#8230;and if that is the hospital&#8230;then that&#8217;s okay with us.</p>
<p>The meeting with Robbie was really awesome!  He is very supportive&#8230;answers every question and brings more hope then I think he realizes.  We talked for over two hours about the process.  Robbie is 40 days post transplant and he says he feel really great!  So promising!!!<br />
We have researched and MD Anderson is the BEST in the country for Stem Cell Transplants.  They do over 700 a year which is remarkable.  They have the very best specialist and doctors that see every kind of cancer. Nothing is &#8216;RARE&#8217; to them.  They have seen it ALL!!!  They have social workers, patient advocates and counselors to help Chris and I on this journey.  We feel very good about our decision to go to MD Anderson. Chris will be receiving the best treatment possible.  Many doctors will review his case&#8230;council with each other and make collective decisions regarding Chris and his recovery and cure.    We feel so blessed to have this opportunity to go to this amazing institution!</p>
<p>The holidays just don&#8217;t matter to me.  The most important thing to me is that Chris and I are together&#8230;and that we take one day at a time.</p>
<p>Amy</p></div>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td height="25">
<hr size="1" /></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textTimeHeader" height="20" valign="top">SUNDAY, NOVEMBER 23, 2008 04:13 PM, CST</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textNormal12">
<div style="overflow: auto;">So&#8230;Today we meet Robbie.  The other Burkitt&#8217;s lymphoma survivor.  He is coming through Pensacola on his way home from MD Anderson and we are going to grab a bite to eat and chat about &#8217;stuff&#8217;.  We are excited to meet him.<br />
The lump is bigger today.  Chris will probably need chemo tomorrow.<br />
We took a long drive together and talked and talked&#8230;we drove out to Perdido beach and brought our dog Oscar.  It was nice to just relax and look out at the beautiful water.<br />
We celebrated our friend Dru&#8217;s 30 birthday last night. I have a feeling this will be the last time we get to really go &#8216;out&#8217; for awhile. But that&#8217;s okay&#8230;because we have 60 plus more years to celebrate with friends!:)<br />
That&#8217;s all today&#8230;we are trying not to let this get us down. FEARLESS, fearless, fearless.<br />
We want to thank you for all the support,gifts and for stopping us in public to introduce yourself.  We have met amazing people along this journey.</p>
<p>Love you guys!</p>
<p>Amy</p></div>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td height="25">
<hr size="1" /></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textTimeHeader" height="20" valign="top">SATURDAY, NOVEMBER 22, 2008 05:31 PM, CST</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textNormal12">
<div style="overflow: auto;">I haven&#8217;t really felt like writing lately because sometimes we just want to feel normal and not have to constantly talk and think about this whole situation.  We are not sure as of Thursday if the lump is growing back.  Chris went to see Dr. Sunnenberg and he said it could be a number of things but we can&#8217;t help to think that maybe it&#8217;s coming back. Chris has an appointment set up for December 3rd in Houston at M.D.Anderson.  He may have to have a little chemo before then to keep things down.  Chris has another appointment with Dr.Sunnenberg on Monday to check things out and see if there are any changes.<br />
We have a wonderful place to stay in Houston which is a relief!  A good friend of mine has a brother that lives there with his girlfriend and they have a guest room for us to use while we are there.  It&#8217;s nice to have a home away from home.  They have been so gracious and sweet to take us in and make us feel welcome in their home.  they live 35 minutes away from M.D.Anderson.</p>
<p>I think Chris and I feel as though the wind was taken out of our sails.  For the first time in a long time we felt like life was getting back to normal then one day we wake up and there the lump is&#8230;right in front of our eyes.  It&#8217;s very heart breaking. Chris says he isn&#8217;t scared or fearful&#8230;just tired of this whole ordeal.  He said today that he feels like he hit his limit.</p>
<p>He&#8217;s been writing a lot and staying busy with work.  We will be leaving Tuesday the 2ndof December.  We are not sure what will happen when we get there.  If we will have to stay for 6 weeks or come home then go back for treatment. It&#8217;s all up in the air and overwhelming.</p>
<p>For now we are praying that there is a solution and that the Stem cell transplant will offer the cure.</p>
<p>Love you guys!</p>
<p>Amy</p></div>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td height="25">
<hr size="1" /></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textTimeHeader" height="20" valign="top">WEDNESDAY, NOVEMBER 12, 2008 10:53 AM, CST</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textNormal12">
<div style="overflow: auto;">Our weekend was wonderful! We had a really relaxing time in Destin ,Florida.  We went to dinner at PF Changs and stayed at a friends condo for a night.<br />
Chris has severe burns on his neck from the radiation. It looks like sun poisoning. This is normal considering the intense regime Chris had over the last 3 weeks.  The AWESOME news is that Dr. Sunnenberg says Chris looks astoundingly good!  For a man that has had 7 rounds of chemo,chicken pox, and 30 rounds of radiation&#8230;.he looks pretty incredible!!!!  The radiation will continue to work for up to two weeks post treatment.<br />
We hopefully figured out our insurance situation but will know more in the next couple of days about the transplant coverage.  Our new policy starts on Dec 1 st.  Dr. Sunnenberg wants to send Chris to M.D Anderson around that time for some testing to see if he is in remission and to speak to a lymphoma specialist.<br />
We feel that he is in remission.  We just need the proof.  These next three weeks we will focus on building Chris&#8217; endurance and getting him as physically fit as possible&#8230;so if he has to have the transplant&#8230;his body will be ready.  We started walking last night&#8230;about three miles.  His diet will be a big component in this whole process. Lot&#8217;s of fresh salads&#8230;protein, fruits, and veggies.<br />
We are almost there!!!  Please keep him in your thoughts and prayers through this next month.We are hoping these test come back&#8230;COMPLETE REMISSION!!!</p>
<p>I want to thank our family as well as&#8230;.Abby,Jill,  and Stephanie for everything!!!</p>
<p>We Love you guys so much!!! Thank you to our friends for supporting us through this crazy time in our lives!</p>
<p>Love, Amy</p></div>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td height="25">
