<tr>
<td height="25">
<hr size="1" /></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textTimeHeader" height="20" valign="top">WEDNESDAY, NOVEMBER 05, 2008 07:56 PM, CST</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textNormal12">
<div style="overflow: auto;">Today was a very heavy day&#8230;.it&#8217;s hard to keep your chin up when you are faced with so much uncertainty. I have to be honest&#8230; Today was a struggle for me.  We spent a large part of our anniversary fighting with the insurance company.  It&#8217;s hard sometimes to see past everything.  I have glimpses of how life used to be&#8230;not a real care in the world&#8230;no stress to really speak about.  Chris and I have always celebrated our love everyday. We&#8217;ve always tried to see who could make the other one the happiest.  So, really our anniversary is just an extension of what we do on a daily basis. I never take his love for granted&#8230;I never have&#8230;I enjoy him so much and he blows me away everyday with his kindness and his sincere heart.  I have always said and feel very strongly that every woman should feel the way Chris makes me feel.  I used to be afraid to speak about this kind of thing because I never wanted to seem like I was boasting&#8230;.But I&#8217;m very proud of the love that we share and I think it is important to express this&#8230;especially today.<br />
We went to his last radiation today&#8230;then we celebrated with a cup of coffee at Starbucks!:)  Chris had his appointment with our yoga friend Linda.  He went for a jog and he said when he got home after his run&#8230;he could tell the color in his skin came back more than ever. We are going to go ahead a meet with the docotors at M.D Anderson.  We are not going to deny ourselves an opportunity to speak with some of the best in the country.  That might happen within the next week.  We will see what they have to say and just perceiver.  What ever it takes.  I said it before and I will say it a million times&#8230;I/we will not stop until we reach remission and CURE!  That is my mission and nothing will stand in my way!</p>
<p>I want to take a minute to thank a couple of people&#8230;First,we received the sweetest anonymous gift .  It was a framed art piece of a couple with strings tied to their hearts and it had the most beautiful poem about love on it.  Thank you&#8230;it was perfect and we will treasure it always.<br />
Thank you to Caroline&#8230;for the Godiva chocolates.  You are so loving and giving and Chris and I appreciate you so much!  Cheryl&#8230;thank you for your help with the insurance info!  You are really a huge support to Chris and I.  Thank you to our friends and to our family&#8230;I hope you know how much you mean to us.  Thank you for putting Chris on all the prayer lists and thinking of him everyday.  We feel the support from all of you&#8230;and we are overwhelmed with gratitude.</p>
<p>Well, now we are going to just sit together and enjoy the rest of today.</p>
<p>I will keep you posted!</p>
<p>We love you guys!</p>
<p>Amy</p></div>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td height="25">
<hr size="1" /></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textTimeHeader" height="20" valign="top">TUESDAY, NOVEMBER 04, 2008 06:36 PM, CST</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textNormal12">
<div style="overflow: auto;">Today was a roller coaster!  Dr. Sunnenberg said that Chris looked great&#8230;his blood counts were fantastic.  Everything looked really good.  He said he was going to solidify things with M.D Anderson and talk to the lymphoma guru&#8230;Dr. Romaguera.   yesterday&#8230;.Out of sheer curiosity&#8230;Chris called our insurance company to check on our coverage regarding the Stem cell Transplant.  To our surprise&#8230;we have a hidden exclusion in our policy that does NOT cover Stem cell Transplants.  Talk about PANIC!  A stem cell transplant can cost $400,00 plus.  M.D Anderson works directly with the insurance company and will refuse treatment when they find out about this exclusion.  So, as an extra precaution we were prepared to cancel our COBRA policy and go on to another policy with the same insurance company that offered better coverage even for pre-existing conditions.  Chris had everything ready to go&#8230;faxed it all over to the company for approval&#8230;AND  then another bomb got dropped on us&#8230;.WE can not sign on with an independent plan until we EXHAUST all 18 months of our COBRA insurance.  We have 13 more months to go!!!!!!!!!!!!!</p>
<p>PANIC! And more PANIC!  Chris even asked the representative this question&#8230;&#8217;So&#8230;you mean to tell me that if this was the only treatment that could save my life&#8230;you would still deny me the Stem Cell Transplant???&#8217;.  The representatives reply was&#8230;&#8217;Yes Sir!&#8217;<br />
How about that!  This is how unbelievably warped the insurance system is.  Hidden exclusions in insurance policy&#8217;s that literally rob people of the opportunity of a CURE!  It makes me sick to my stomach!<br />
We are overwhelmed with every emotion you can imagine!  The only thing I can say is&#8230;I pray to God that Chris is in remission.<br />
We are working on a back up plan.  And we won&#8217;t stop until we get Chris what he needs for his cure!</p>
<p>I ask that all of you keep him in your thoughts and prayers over the next few days!  His last radiation is tomorrow.  Our fingers are crossed and we are hoping for the very best outcome!</p>
<p>Tomorrow is our 3 year wedding anniversary.  The perfect day for a miracle!</p>
<p>Amy</p></div>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td height="25">
<hr size="1" /></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textTimeHeader" height="20" valign="top">MONDAY, NOVEMBER 03, 2008 07:12 PM, CST</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textNormal12">
<div style="overflow: auto;">We got a phone call from Dr Sunnenberg&#8217;s nurse today and he wants to send Chris to M.D Anderson for the Stem cell Transplant.  We have our big meeting with him tomorrow.  We will go over the &#8216;plan&#8217;.  Most likely we will go to Houston and Chris will receive a series of tests.  All the testing will take about a week.  We will move forward based the results of his tests.  As far as we know&#8230;Chris COULD already be in remission. His last PET Scan was BEFORE his 30 radiation treatments.  So, there is a very good chance that the rest of the tumor that you see in he scan is GONE!!  That might change things a little.  We are not sure that MD Anderson will go forward with a stem cell transplant if Chris is in remission.   That is a question we will ask Dr. Sunnenberg tomorrow.  If they decide not to do it&#8230;we may see if Chris can harvest his stem cells NOW and have them frozen at MD Anderson&#8230;Just in case he needs them later.  That is another question we will ask.<br />
Let me just say&#8230;we have learned so much about insurance and what to ask for in the future.  F.Y.I&#8230;Here are some things to ask and look for in your policy:</p>
<p>1) Cancer coverage<br />
2)Exclusions in your policy&#8230;such as Stem cell transplant<br />
3)Disability policy<br />
4) in patient and out patient coverage amount</p>
<p>We learned the HARD way&#8230;make sure you have this coverage in your policy.  Chris was healthy, 28 years old,worked out regularly,ate healthy.  You just never know.  It&#8217;s better to be safe then sorry.</p>
<p>We will know more tomorrow and I will keep you guys posted.</p>
<p>Thank you for all of your sweet comments and support. We honestly couldn&#8217;t get through this without all of you.  Every comment you leave&#8230;inspires us to stay strong and to keep going! We are praying for remission.  That&#8217;s all we are focused on. We are embracing health!!!:)</p>
<p>Goodnight!  Love you guys!</p>
<p>Amy</p></div>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td height="25">
<hr size="1" /></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textTimeHeader" height="20" valign="top">FRIDAY, OCTOBER 31, 2008 08:17 AM, CDT</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textNormal12">
<div style="overflow: auto;">Well&#8230;so far so good!:)  We saw the radiation doctor( not sure what his proper title is) yesterday.  He felt around on Chris&#8217; neck and said that it looked GREAT!  He said he looks( and feels) tumors all day long and Chris&#8217; neck doesn&#8217;t feel like there is a mass at all!  No tumor!  Now, there may be residual cells left behind that could certainly turn into a tumor and this is why we are proceeding with a Stem cell Transplant. Chris has come so far and been through so much that we can&#8217;t stop now.  We are almost there!!!<br />
Hearing the doctor say&#8217;it looks good&#8230;I don&#8217;t feel a tumor&#8217;&#8230;is like music to our ears!  We still need a CT scan to prove that everything is gone&#8230;and that will definitely  be a big day for us!!!  Chris has been dealing with this spot on his neck since last December!  We can&#8217;t wait to hear those words&#8217; YOU ARE IN REMISSION&#8217;!!!!<br />
He has 6 more radiation treatments left and we pray that it melts the last of the bad cells away!  Dr. Sunnenberg said that there was a case of Burkitts that did chemo and radiation therapy ( like Chris) and he went in to remission just from that!<br />
This has been such a crazy year for us&#8230;we have had a lot of good days and a lot of bad days&#8230;but we are getting through it!<br />
I&#8217;ll keep you posted!</p>
<p>Love, Amy</p></div>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td height="25">
<hr size="1" /></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textTimeHeader" height="20" valign="top">MONDAY, OCTOBER 27, 2008 01:03 PM, CDT</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textNormal12">
<div style="overflow: auto;">We heard from Robbie (The other Burkitt&#8217;s survivor)&#8230;I can&#8217;t believe we found him!!!!  Dr.Sunnenberg said we needed to find another &#8216;Chris Blok&#8217; somewhere in the world&#8230;and we found him!!!!!<br />
He is receiving treatment at MD Anderson and gave us the names of his doctors. Dr. Sunnenberg is affiliated with mD Anderson and has access to all his information.<br />
Another crazy thing is that&#8230;. He had the same doctor that Chris had at Emory&#8230;Dr. Flowers.   I can&#8217;t tell you how relieved we are to have found someone with localized stage one Burkitt&#8217;s in the neck area.  Robbie&#8217;s did not spread either&#8230;like typical Burkitt&#8217;s. The similarities are endless!<br />
He is so helpful and has offered to speak with Chris and I about anything treatment related at anytime.  I am so grateful    We are going to take his info into Dr. Sunnenberg tomorrow. I can&#8217;t wait to see what he says!!!!</p>
<p>Nite!<br />
Amy</p></div>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td height="25">
<hr size="1" /></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textTimeHeader" height="20" valign="top">MONDAY, OCTOBER 27, 2008 01:03 PM, CDT</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textNormal12">
<div style="overflow: auto;">We had such a great weekend with friends!  It was beautiful weather and so relaxing!  Chris and I needed to reconnect with friends and have this amazing down time.  Over the weekend ( Sunday) I started to do my obsessive researching again&#8230;which I have not allowed myself to do for quite sometime because it tends to create a lot of stress for me.  I read so many abstracts, and medical reports&#8230;all the good the bad and the ugly.  It can be very overwhelming.  But I was so driven to research this time.  I always feel like, just maybe, I will stumble across one little piece of info that could change everything.  I read alot about spontaneous remission, which is a real medical term, that is used when people go into remission from all kinds of random things.  There are hundreds,and hundreds possibly even thousands of reports about cases of spontaneous remission and about 32% of them are lymphoma. Interesting!  I found several on Burkitts lymphoma.  A spontaneous remission happened to a girl with Burkitts who got the measles. Then, after that her tumor disappeared.  I was so blown away by this amazing phenomenon.<br />
Well today I felt the same urge to get back on the internet.  And I ran across a story that gave me chills from head to toe. It&#8217;s about a guy, who lives in Atlanta who is about Chris&#8217; age&#8230;that had Burkitt&#8217;s,localized stage one, in his neck.  He just finished his Stem Cell  transplant and he has a blog (just like Chris)  that talks about his journey.It was so parallel to his situation that it blew us away. I have chills just thinking about it because the story is as if Chris was writing about his own experience.   There is something incredible that happens when you find another human being has a story like yours.  Chris e-mailed him right away.   I hope he responds. I will keep you guys posted.</p>
<p>Chris is doing great.  he said he feels like the area on his neck gets firm and soft. It changes from time to time and has done this from the beginning. i am not sure what this means.<br />
He had his radiation appointment this morning and is going for another this afternoon. he also has a yogic breathing session with Linda.  It&#8217;s about an hour of  guided deep, cleansing breath.  Perfect for someone going through all that he is going through.<br />
He will have his blood drawn tomorrow to check his levels. Last time they looked pretty good.  Red counts were still a little low.  Dr. Sunnenberg says he has &#8216;elastic&#8217; bone marrow!  I guess that&#8217;s a good thing! We&#8217;ll take it!<br />
I&#8217;m a little scared about the whole process that lies ahead of us.  I am praying that it goes perfect and Chris  will do SO well!  I ask that you all keep him in your thoughts and prayers over the next week.( and i know you are) We are hoping that the radiation will really shrink things down to nothing.<br />
This has been the craziest journey.  It&#8217;s challenges you on every level.   He is the bravest man I know.  He faces everything, every piece of uncertainty with courage and strength.  He refuses to identify with anything going on. Chris just has this attitude of&#8217; let&#8217;s get on with it&#8230;. so that I can get on with my incredible life&#8217;.  There is no bitterness&#8230;or why me.  I am just in awe of him.  He inspires me everyday to live a life of more purpose, and strength.</p>
<p>We love you guys!<br />
Thank you for your hugs and support.  We appreciate all the love we receive from everyone.  There are no words to express our gratitude.</p>
<p>Amy</p></div>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td height="25">
<hr size="1" /></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textTimeHeader" height="20" valign="top">SATURDAY, OCTOBER 25, 2008 12:10 PM, CDT</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textNormal12">
<div style="overflow: auto;">We met with Dr.Sunnenberg yesterday.  It was a good visit overall but there are still some unanswered questions.  He was VERY happy with how Chris&#8217; neck looked and told us that the oncologist that he conferenced with didn&#8217;t think radiation would keep the tumor down.  It was a shot in the dark&#8230;. But surprise surprise&#8230;It&#8217;s working! We are thrilled!  We are still waiting to find out if we are going to Emory for a Stem Cell Transplant or if we are going to NCI.  I&#8217;m not really clear on ALL the details but I guess it matters which type of Stem Cell Chris needs and how involved it will be.  It would be nice to do the preparatory chemotherapy here at home&#8230;then drive 4 1/2 hours to Atlanta for Stem Cell collection then the transplant. Then there is a possibility that they will let Chris recover back at home at Sacred Heart.  I&#8217;m not sure how all that will work and it was all kind of mentioned lightly in our meeting with Dr. Sunnenberg.  Frankly, it scares me a little to  have Chris leave Atlanta&#8230;if anything were to go wrong&#8230;I wouldn&#8217;t want Chris to get an infection in transition.  I&#8217;m just trusting that everything will workout EXACTLY the way it supposed&#8230;.The transplant is going to be perfect!<br />
We are thinking that we are going with an AUTO transplant,which is much safer. They will extract Chris&#8217; stem cells from him and then give them back.  Dr.Sunnenberg wanted to speak with Dr. Dunleavy at NCI before making that call for sure.  there are many risk factors with an Allo stem cell( someone else&#8217;s&#8230;possibly his sister&#8217;s&#8230;if she&#8217;s a perfect match) but there are a lot of benefits too.  there is a 1 in 5 chance that his sister will be compatible.<br />
Chris feels really good!  We have enjoyed this down time so much. Life has felt somewhat normal the last two weeks.  It&#8217;s been so refreshing and will give us the strength we need to get through the transplant.  His last radiation treatment is on our 3 year wedding anniversary&#8230;November 5th. How fitting!!!<br />
Today is my dad&#8217;s birthday.  And he and I did the breast cancer 5K in honor of my mother who passed away from breast cancer last December.  It was very emotional for my dad and I &#8230;but it was so sweet and incredibly moving!  There were, what seemed to be thousands of people there!  And SO many survivors!  I believe that when we find the cure for one cancer it will unlock the door for other cures!  I can&#8217;t wait for us to totally annihilate this disease.<br />
So for now Chris is still doing radiation twice a day&#8230;then seeing the doctor next Tuesday.</p>
<p>Just real quick&#8230;.I got to meet the guys in radiation.  They are hilarious!!!  One of them was showing me the way the radiation machine works and how it targets the area on Chris&#8217; neck and I made the comment that the machine was soooo precise!  The tech (who has a very thick New York accent) replied&#8230;. &#8216; well, this isn&#8217;t pin the tail on the donkey,my friend&#8217;!  I laughed so hard  I think I almost wet my pants!  Chris and I have laughed and laughed about that!</p>
<p>Well, I will leave you with that story!:)</p>
<p>Hope all of you are having a beautiful weekend and thank you so much for everything!</p>
<p>We love you guys!</p>
<p>Amy</p></div>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td height="25">
<hr size="1" /></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textTimeHeader" height="20" valign="top">WEDNESDAY, OCTOBER 22, 2008 06:51 PM, CDT</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textNormal12">
<div style="overflow: auto;">Chris had his treatments today.  He is getting twice the amount that the average person going through this would get and he still thinks it&#8217;s a piece of cake. Aside from some lite fatigue&#8230;he has really done well with the whole thing. The techs explained to Chris that the beam is at it&#8217;s strongest point when it hits the tumor.  This is why it doesn&#8217;t completely fry his skin.  It can still cause dryness and some irritation&#8230;but so far so good.  We went to the gym again today and we are just ENJOYING every healthy minute!!!! Chris amazes me with his energy!<br />
We called Dr. Sunnenbergs office to see if there is anything we need to do to get the ball rolling for his Stem Cell transplant.  (Paper work,testing etc)  We don&#8217;t want there to be any lag time.<br />
Basically&#8230;after radiation,he may be tested once more then he will do preparatory chemo here OR perhaps at NCI for 2 rounds then the third round will be the mega dose that will kill his stem cells&#8230;.. then they will give them back, creating new clean blood for Chris.  The whole process should take 4-6 weeks. We have a friend who did it in 16 days.  The main concern is infection.  He will have no defense,so it&#8217;s crucial to protect him from potential threats for infection.<br />
Chris and I have set up a conference with a man named Gordon who has gone through all of this before after a relapse of mantel cell lymphoma.  He is doing well and knows first hand how things will go for us.<br />
We have met some pretty incredible people along the way.  Thanks to Cheryl (and Kyler),Danny, Gordon, Jolly and Sara&#8230;not to mention all of the great people on the lymphoma forum&#8230;Chris and I have had all of our questions answered quickly.  Everyone is so helpful and compassionate.  It&#8217;s been amazing.</p>
<p>Today was a good day!:)</p>
<p>We want to send prayers to the Sparkman family who lost their precious little boy to lymphoblastic lymphoma last night.  Michael was such an inspiration to us and so courageous!!!  We are sending you hugs and hoping you are able to find some peace in all this grief.</p>
<p>We love you guys!<br />
Thank you for you sweet cards and comments&#8230;.you have no idea what it does for our/his spirit!</p>
<p>Goodnight!</p>
<p>Amy</p></div>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td height="25">
<hr size="1" /></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textTimeHeader" height="20" valign="top">TUESDAY, OCTOBER 21, 2008 06:32 PM, CDT</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textNormal12">
<div style="overflow: auto;">Not much to talk about really&#8230;which is a good thing!  We had a great day.  Chris went for his RADS today and was telling me about some of the funny conversations that he has with the techs.  It&#8217;s pretty entertaining to say the least.  He said they seem like really nice guys&#8230;the whole process is really quite pleasant.  Chris and I had a nice lunch outside and then went for a long walk at sunset today.  The weather is just perfect, so we are trying to enjoy the natural air as much as possible.  Days like today are priceless.<br />
He will go for blood work and to see the doc on Friday.  He&#8217;s going to have a session with my friend Linda the yoga instructor on Thursday.  So far things are going well and his neck looks pretty good.  It&#8217;s hard to tell sometimes if things are shrinking because of the scar tissue.  I am constantly looking at it for any changes and so far it looks great!!! I am hoping that the radiation will mop up all the last bit of this tiny little tumor.  And then if we do a Stem cell transplant as an insurance policy then that&#8217;s fine with us.<br />
We ask that everyone imagine that tiny black dot on his PET scan ( pictured in the photo gallery) GONE.  If we all are focused on it disappearing and praying for remission&#8230;I have no doubt that it will happen!<br />
The radiation is pretty powerful stuff!  My friend had a large tumor in her stomach&#8230;MALT lymphoma and the radiation alone put her in remission.  Burkitt&#8217;s lymphoma is much more aggressive&#8230;but Chris has had 7 chemos&#8230;on top of 30 radiation treatments&#8230;.I&#8217;m thinking it might not have a prayer!</p>
<p>Well that&#8217;s all I have tonight!  Although, I do want to say one more thing&#8230;we are sending our love and prayers to Michael Sparkman and his family tonight&#8230;he is a 7 year old that is struggling for his life and has a very aggressive lymphoma.  You can find his profile on the caring bridge site under Michael Sparkman.  We are praying that the family find peace in this most difficult time.</p>
<p>Love you guys and thank you for your wonderful comments and support&#8230;We are so grateful for all of you!</p>
<p>Goodnight!</p>
<p>Amy</p></div>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td height="25">
<hr size="1" /></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textTimeHeader" height="20" valign="top">MONDAY, OCTOBER 20, 2008 06:30 PM, CDT</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textNormal12">
<div style="overflow: auto;">Well, we had our appointment today with Dr. Sunnenberg.    We were able to see the PET/CT Scans and there was a huge difference in the size of the tumor. It&#8217;s MUCH smaller! It looks like its about a forth of what it was to begin with.  Chris started his radiation and so far so good.  It hasn&#8217;t shrunk the tumor but it&#8217;s definitely keeping it down.  Now, some people say that it will fry the hell out of it and others think it will just keep it at bay. So, it&#8217;s hard to say exactly what is going to happen.  Chris is most likely going to have a Stem Cell Transplant.  We are waiting to hear back from NCI.  Dr.Sunnenberg is going to see Chris every Monday and Friday to take his blood samples and check the area on his neck.  He will keep a close eye on him for the next two weeks.<br />
We are staying super hopeful!  There is still a lot on the table.  The weeks to come will map out our plan of action.</p>
<p>We ask that our friends and family pray that Chris is able to achieve remission very soon!<br />
He feels great!  And he looks wonderful.  All side effects have subsided. Chris went to the gym today&#8230;he feels really good.  The radiation is a piece of cake compared to chemo.   That really kicked his butt!!!</p>
<p>We love you and we will keep you posted!</p>
<p>Amy</p></div>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td height="25">
<hr size="1" /></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textTimeHeader" height="20" valign="top">FRIDAY, OCTOBER 17, 2008 04:22 PM, CDT</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textNormal12">
<div style="overflow: auto;">Today was a good day.  Chris had a PET scan at 7:30 this morning and had to wear his mask for 20 minutes during the scan. That part wasn&#8217;t fun but it went well overall.  He also had his two radiation treatments&#8230;one at 8:oo and one at 2:30.  I noticed the area on his neck looks a little inflamed.  I don&#8217;t know if it&#8217;s inflammation or if it&#8217;s growing.  I&#8217;m trying to just stay neutral until we meet with Dr.Sunnenberg on Monday. Something tells me we will have to have another chemo treatment soon but we will see.  It could just be the radiation causing  the inflammation.<br />
We are looking forward to the weekend.  His counts are excellent which means we can go to the movies or dinner or whatever we want to do.  It &#8217;s such a great feeling to have freedom to live your life.<br />
I went to meet with my friend today who is an advanced yoga instructor/life coach/energy healer&#8230;shes just AWESOME!  She has helped me so much !  There is an abundance of fear when you or someone you love deeply is faced with cancer.  It&#8217;s easy to get swept up in the fear and neglect yourself.  It felt good to relax and recharge so that I can be fully &#8216;present&#8217; for Chris.  My friend is going to work with Chris as well.  I think we both will benefit from this time with her.  She teaches a lot of breathing techniques and Tai yoga massage&#8230;stretching, etc.<br />
We are looking forward to our meeting on Monday.  This should be very informative.  I will keep you all posted!</p>
<p>I want to take a minute to say thank you to all of the people who have reached out to Chris and myself.  We are so blown away by the generosity of complete strangers, who have read Chris story.  We are thankful for our friends and family for supporting us in ways that are immeasurable.</p>
<p>Thank you , Thank you&#8230;from the bottom of our hearts!</p>
<p>Love, Amy</p></div>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td height="25">
<hr size="1" /></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textTimeHeader" height="20" valign="top">THURSDAY, OCTOBER 16, 2008 06:16 PM, CDT</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textNormal12">
<div style="overflow: auto;">Nothing confuses me more than &#8216;radiation therapy&#8217; and the whole concept of burning cancer from the inside out. Just so weird and I can&#8217;t really wrap my brain around it.<br />
I&#8217;m going to be really honest&#8230;things are very confusing right now&#8230;I feel like I do not have one ounce of a grip on what exactly is going on. Which quite frankly is terrifying&#8230;because I&#8217;ve always had a pretty good idea of what is going on and where we are headed.<br />
This is what I do know though&#8230;.<br />
We have a meeting scheduled with Dr. Sunnenberg Monday morning to discuss our plan. Chris has a PET scan scheduled tomorrow morning at 7:30 am&#8230;geeesh!  He had two radiation treatments today and it feels a little tender in the area they treated.  These are the options:</p>
<p>1)Radiation for 3 weeks then chemo<br />
2)Radiation and chemo at the same time<br />
3) radiation then stem cell transplant<br />
4) Radiation and chemo then Stem cell transplant</p>
<p>So&#8230;these are our options.  The stem cell transplant will involve Chris and I moving up to NCI for 4-6 weeks.  Chris will have to take a leave of absence most likely because I don&#8217;t think he will be able to work.  He works from home&#8230;so it&#8217;s possible he will feel okay some of the time to work a little.   We won&#8217;t know until we get there and see how he feels.<br />
It&#8217;s just too stressful to think about honestly.  It&#8217;s in Gods hands.  I just want Chris back to his new self&#8230;and full of energy!  Whatever it takes to get us there&#8230;is what we will have to do!</p>
<p>I&#8217;ll keep you posted!</p>
<p>love, Amy</p></div>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td height="25">
<hr size="1" /></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textTimeHeader" height="20" valign="top">WEDNESDAY, OCTOBER 15, 2008 07:03 PM, CDT</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textNormal12">
<div style="overflow: auto;">Chris woke me up this morning and said&#8230;we have an appointment for radiation at 9:30 am.  Dr. Sunnenberg doesn&#8217;t waste anytime.  When he says GO&#8230;you just GO!  So out of bed and back to the hospital we went for consult with the radiation doctor to talk about our goals.  This was an interesting conversation that went something like this&#8230;.we are giving you radiation TODAY.  I&#8217;ve only done this once before on a guy your age&#8230;15 years ago with Burkitt&#8217;s lymphoma. Who is alive and well today.  This will buy us sometime before you go for your Stem Cell Transplant!!!!!!!!!!!!!  Okay&#8230;I know we have talked about possibilities of Stem Cell&#8230;. but we never said &#8216;for sure&#8217; this is what we are doing.  So the roller coaster continues.<br />
I just sat there in shock&#8230;.and asked if this is what Dr.Sunnenberg said???  He informed Chris and I that he had a big conference with several doctors around the world&#8230;FLowers, Sunnenberg, Dunleavy , and their colleges and they are ALL in agreement&#8230;Stem Cell is the way to go.  I asked him IF Chris goes into remission from radiation and chemo would we still consider Stem Cell at that point?  His answer was YES!  Okay&#8230;whatever it takes.  At this point we surrender to the process and we will do whatever it takes to CURE Chris of this awful disease.<br />
So after our consult Chris went back for his treatment.  They fit him for his face mask&#8230;which is pretty crazy stuff by the way and looks a bit like &#8216;Hell Raiser&#8217;( that guy with the needles in his face.)  It&#8217;s a creepy mask.  The mask snaps down onto the table while Chris&#8217; face is in it and they use beams to burn out the lymph node and cancer.  It is basically an internal sunburn.  It&#8217;s a 10 minute process&#8230;thank god.<br />
You know&#8230;everyday brings something new&#8230;you just have to roll with it.</p>
<p>Chris and I had an incredible conversation yesterday about the things we want to accomplish in life&#8230;</p>
<p>Going through this process,whether you are the patient or the caregiver&#8230;one thing remains the same-and that is the desire to live life to the fullest.  We want to do it ALL when Chris goes into remission and is cured.  It&#8217;s almost as if someone turned up the volume on life and it speaks louder to us than ever before!  Everything we have ever talked about from going to Europe to having a child is right in the forefront of our minds and hearts.  There is NO time to waste! The quote&#8217; life is what happens when you are making plans&#8217;&#8230; has more meaning than ever.  Life did happened when we were making plans&#8230;and unfortunately they stayed just that&#8230;.PLANS.<br />
Those days are over for Chris and I&#8230;the days of planning and not doing&#8230; are in the past.  We are on a mission to experience ALL  the wonderful things that life has to offer.</p>
<p>There is a powerful feeling that comes over me when I grab Chris&#8217; hand and he grabs mine as we walk into each doctors appointment,hospital visit , challenge. It&#8217;s a brave fearlessness that happens the minute we grab hands and with our chin up&#8230;we walk right into the unknown.  We have always known but now we have proven that anything is possible with love&#8230;.anything!</p>
<p>So..who knows what tomorrow will bring but we will keep you posted.  Chris will get radiation twice a day, 5 days a week for 3 weeks.  Then we have no idea what is going to happen&#8230;Chemo? or Stem cell? or Both?  We shall see!</p>
<p>Love you guys!  Thank you for EVERYTHING!!!!  We could never express our gratitude in this life time!</p>
<p>Amy</p></div>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td height="25">
<hr size="1" /></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textTimeHeader" height="20" valign="top">TUESDAY, OCTOBER 14, 2008 07:14 PM, CDT</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textNormal12">
<div style="overflow: auto;">I&#8217;m so tired&#8230;. I can barely hold my eyes open. The last five days have been so intense.<br />
Chris finally broke his fever&#8230;.his chicken pox are healing nicely and his blood counts are finally going up not down.  Dr. Sunnenberg came by to check on Chris this morning and was pleased with how he was progressing. Dr. E (can&#8217;t pronounce his name) the infectious disease Doctor came by and said he was free to go home! Yea!  Then we got a phone call from Dr. Sunnenberg after he left the hospital letting us know that he was able to speak to our oncologist at Emory University&#8230;Dr Flowers and he said based on the power point presentation of pictures that Chris put together&#8230;.Dr. Flowers and his colleges in the lymphoma department at the Windship Cancer Institute were VERY PLEASED!  He said Chris was doing very well with treatment and thought we should start radiation&#8230;. then do the last four rounds of chemo after radiation.  There is NO way to do both at the same time because as you can see&#8230;the chemo treatments are VERY hard on Chris&#8217; body.  So we would take a break, radiate and then finish the last four treatments.</p>
<p>Chris had his Cat scan today of his neck, chest, abdomen and groin area.  The test came back PERFECT&#8230;.still stage one, localized in the neck area.  It has not traveled and the chemo is working!  Today was a good day!  Good news all the way around.  We are still not ruling out a Stem cell Transplant.  We have a lot to think about. My wish is that we get our remission with treatment locally. That&#8217;s my wish.  BUT we are willing to do whatever our doctors recommend because, so far they have been amazing and they have saved my husbands life by giving his the correct diagnoses and proper treatment&#8230;So,what they say GOES at this point.</p>
<p>Chris and I want to thank everyone for their comments!  You really have no idea just how much we look forward to reading them out loud to each other.  It brightens everyday and gives us both the strength we need to press through the day.  We also want to say thank you for your donations on our cureforchris.com website.  We are truly blown away by your support and your kindness.</p>
<p>We love you guys so much!</p>
<p>Amy</p></div>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td height="25">
<hr size="1" /></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textTimeHeader" height="20" valign="top">MONDAY, OCTOBER 13, 2008 08:54 AM, CDT</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textNormal12">
<div style="overflow: auto;">Chris STILL has a low grade fever. It stays between 99.1 and 99.6.  Dr. Sunnenberg came in today&#8230;.he LOVED the way Chris&#8217; neck looked!!! YEA!  But he was not happy with the fact that he had chicken pox, fischers, and no blood counts. So, needless to say&#8230;we will be hanging out in the hospital for awhile&#8230;at least until Chris has some defense.  He got more platelet&#8217;s last night and it brought them up quite a bit!  His transfusion was pointless!  The 2 bags of blood did absolutely nothing!  BUMMER!</p>
<p>Good news is&#8230;Chris looks good&#8230;.he&#8217;s eating great!  He&#8217;s sleeping and his spirits are high!!!!  We laugh and watch TV&#8230;talk and joke around trying to entertain ourselves.  It&#8217;s not so bad!  I mean of coarse we would rather be doing other things that are MUCH more fun&#8230;BUT it could be worse and we feel really blessed!<br />
He is still in contact isolation and can not leave his room. Everyone has to &#8217;suit up&#8217; and wear a mask&#8230;etc.  Except me:)!   He&#8217;s used to my kooties! LOL!  Just Kidding!  Although I do wear a mask from time to time&#8230;just in case!</p>
<p>Chris is still getting round the clock antibiotics and I think they are helping because his mouth soars are healing and so are his chicken pox on his face.  YEA!</p>
<p>Overall&#8230;he is doing fine!  Hopefully today will be uneventful and he can go home soon!</p>
<p>Love, Amy</p></div>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td height="25">
<hr size="1" /></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textTimeHeader" height="20" valign="top">SUNDAY, OCTOBER 12, 2008 12:12 PM, CDT</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textNormal12">
<div style="overflow: auto;">Chris was in good spirits today&#8230;when I opened my eyes this morning he said&#8230;&#8217;Good Morning beautiful&#8217;&#8230;and I melted. He has the most sincere and loving spirit I have ever encountered.  I love this man will all that I have!  I can&#8217;t imagine not being by his side through this.  I do not feel that the lymphoma is a blessing ( and let me stress that) BUT however&#8230;I do feel blessed to have found a love so deep within myself for another human being.  Nothing can take that away from me&#8230;and that is the biggest gift in all of this.</p>
<p>Chris had &#8216;Rigors&#8217; last night. For those of you who don&#8217;t know what these are&#8230;They are intense shakes almost convulsions.  It&#8217;s scary because they are obviously involuntary and uncontrollable.  I buzzed the nurse to come right away. In the mean time I told Chris to focus on his breath&#8230;.slow inhalations and slow exhalations and we were breathing together&#8230;.I bundled him in blankets and we continued breathing and i kept telling him that &#8216; he was okay&#8217; and for him to keep telling himself&#8230;&#8217;I'm Okay&#8217;.  After he got warm and we did our breathing&#8230;30 minutes had gone by and FINALLY the nurse came in and said she never got our message.  SCARY HUH?<br />
What I have realized through all of this&#8230;is that fear and panic can take you down a scary road.  The minute you focus on your breath, close you eyes and go within and tell yourself mentally&#8230;that you are okay and truly believe that you ARE&#8230;.Things can turn around in an instant and you have won half the battle!!!<br />
Chris and I have used this tool countless times through this experience.  It&#8217;s such a powerful thing to have&#8230;and the amazing thing is that everybody has it&#8230;they just don&#8217;t realize it,and the fear takes over.</p>
<p>Needless to say,Chris was able to sleep and did not require medication to calm his Rigors.</p>
<p>His counts are continuing to drop but we refuse to let this scare us or take over our thoughts.  There is a solution and a RIGHT answer to bring his counts up and for Chris to continue on his chemo schedule.</p>
<p>His heart rate is 120.It&#8217;s high but his body is under so much stress and is fighting hard to come back up.</p>
<p>The infectious disease Doctor came in this morning to check out Chris and see if this rash was in fact shingles or something else.  WEll&#8230;.it&#8217;s just chicken pox!!!!!  Can you believe it&#8230;at 28years old&#8230;.my husband has chicken pox.  We just laughed about it&#8230;I mean what else can you do, right?<br />
Here&#8217;s the blessing&#8230;Chicken pox can be deadly in adults &#8230;especially cancer patients and can lead to pneumonia.  The blessing is that all along Chris had been receiving the perfect antibiotic through his chemo regimen, that never allowed it to progress into FULL blown adult chicken pox!!! PHEEEEW! Thank you God!!!</p>
<p>We ask that you keep Chris in your thoughts and prayers&#8230;so that his counts come up and we can proceed with treatment.  Time is of the essence in his case.  Every day counts!!!</p>
<p>We want to thank our family for pulling together for us and supporting us in ways we never imagined!  Thank you to all our friends and people we don&#8217;t know personally&#8230;who have left us the most amazing and thoughtful messages.  We are truly awestruck by the love we feel from everyone.</p>
<p>We love you!</p>
<p>Amy</p></div>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td height="25">
<hr size="1" /></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textTimeHeader" height="20" valign="top">SATURDAY, OCTOBER 11, 2008 06:23 PM, CDT</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textNormal12">
<div style="overflow: auto;">UGH!  What a hectic night and day.  Last night, Chris and I had my dad over for dinner and Chris got to eat his steak.  After dad left Chris took a nice relaxing bath then we laid in bed to watch a movie.  I reached over to kiss Chris and I noticed his lips were on FIRE!!!  I asked him if he was okay&#8230;and he said &#8216;yes&#8230;why&#8217;?  I told him he was on fire and we needed to check his temperature.  So&#8230;we did and it was 101.6!!!!!!!!  YIKES!<br />
So I gave him some Tylenol and ice under his arms and behind his neck and we called the doctor.  The doctor said to give it an hour.  We checked it every hour and it did continue to go down slightly.  By midnight his temp was 99.1 and stayed that way ALL night and morning.<br />
99.1 is still a low grade fever though and is still something to be concerned about, so I asked Chris to call the doc and get her feedback on what to do.  She instructed him to go to the ER&#8230;.THE &#8216;ER&#8217;!!!!  Mind you&#8230;he has no White blood cells, no red blood cells and no platelets.  The ER is the LAST place he needs to go.  But Chris wore his mask and showed up at the ER around 9:30am.  They checked his blood levels to find that instead of going up&#8230;they were plummeting.  His fever was 98.5 but they decided to keep him because of his levels.<br />
So we are now back on the 2nd floor in our room for an indefinite amount of time.He&#8217;s getting another blood transfusion, antibiotics and fluids.  Who knows when we will be out of here.  We were so looking forward to a nice relaxing weekend before he had to come back to receive his next dose of chemo&#8230;OH WELL!  I&#8217;m just glad that he is being taken care of and soon he will feel better.<br />
The infectious disease people are coming to see him tomorrow to figure out his shingles situation.  I don&#8217;t think he is contagious but we want to make absolutely sure what we are dealing with.  His blood and cultures came back fine, so who knows what is going on and why he&#8217;s running this fever.<br />
They gave him two percacett for the pain he&#8217;s been having with something called &#8216;fischers&#8217; and I will  spare you all the details.  My poor baby has had everything from shingles to rashes to nose bleeds and everything in between.  After he took the percacetts he looked at me and said&#8230;&#8217; I feel amazing&#8217;!  I haven&#8217;t heard Chris say this in months!</p>
<p>Well, here we are&#8230;another weekend in the hospital!  Hopefully they will get him back in balance and we will be able to have a couple days at home before we head back in on Wednesday!</p>
<p>Love you guys!</p>
<p>Amy</p></div>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td height="25">
<hr size="1" /></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textTimeHeader" height="20" valign="top">FRIDAY, OCTOBER 10, 2008 11:33 AM, CDT</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textNormal12">
<div style="overflow: auto;">Well&#8230;..Our morning started off with a nose bleed that wouldn&#8217;t stop. Immediately I knew Chris&#8217; red counts and platelet&#8217;s were low&#8230;we didn&#8217;t have to see the doctor to figure that much out.<br />
We got to the doctors office and had his blood tests done. Sure enough&#8230;he has no white cells,no red cells and no platelet&#8217;s. The crazy but wonderful part, is that he feels great!( aside form the nose bleed). So needless to say&#8230;NO chemo today! Dr. Sunnenburg would have given Chris his chemo today because he&#8217;s tough on Chris and likes to &#8216;beat him up&#8217; because Chris is young and resilient. But, we thought it was best that he have more time to recover before he got smacked again with something else. He&#8217;s had everything from shingles to mouth soars to nose bleeds and MORE ( that I won&#8217;t mention) in just one week. So, his body needs a break.</p>
<p>So we are scheduled first thing Monday morning for Chemo and then maybe back into the hospital on Wednesday for 4-5 days of more chemo (hyper-cvad part B with the new drug).</p>
<p>So, Thats all for now. We are planning on having a nice relaxing weekend&#8230;enjoy the weather and get ready for the week ahead of us. I&#8217;m going to go get him a steak for dinner tonight. He needs iron&#8230;so whatever it takes!!!!:) Chris is so excited because he never gets to eat steak&#8230;.poor guy!</p>
<p>Chris and I love all of the sweet messages, cards and flowers, fruit, and gifts. We feel so blessed to have all of you in our life. Thank you from the bottom of our hearts! We/he couldn&#8217;t get through this without all of you!!!</p>
<p>Love, Amy</p></div>
</td>
</tr>
