<td class="textTimeHeader" height="20" valign="top">THURSDAY, OCTOBER 09, 2008 11:24 PM, CDT</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textNormal12">
<div style="overflow: auto;">Please visit www.cureforchris.com. This site is still under construction but should be fully functional over the next few days.</p>
<p>Love, Amy</p></div>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textNormal12"></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td height="25">
<hr size="1" /></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textTimeHeader" height="20" valign="top">THURSDAY, OCTOBER 09, 2008 04:03 PM, CDT</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textNormal12">
<div style="overflow: auto;">Last night was a good night.  We both slept well and woke up refreshed.  YEAH!!!!:)</p>
<p>Chris&#8217; blood counts are super low. He got his shot yesterday, so hopefully they will increase over the next couple of days. Tomorrow they will check his levels again, and if they are high enough they will proceed with his chemo protocol and administer a shot of Vincristine ( a tumor shrinking drug). Next Tuesday we will see Dr.Sunnenburg again so that he can evaluate the area where the lump was and we can make a decision on which direction we will go in. Next Tuesday will be a pivotal point in our journey.</p>
<p>I spoke with my my dear friend Cheryl&#8230;whose son went through the same treatment as Chris and had the same lymphoma also. She reassure me that the Stem Cell Transplant is SO doable and not too scary. I feel confidant that if this is the path we chose to take, that Chris will pull through just fine. It&#8217;s a remarkable technology that gives people a second chance at life&#8230;&#8217;Cancer Free&#8217;.<br />
I think that we are finally surrendering to the process and trusting our oncologist. Instead of resisting the things that sound scary and trying to control and question everything. Although I will always question everyone from nurses to doctors when I feel it is necessary. Dr. Sunnenberg is really incredible and we are so thankful for Paula and her husband for getting us on his schedule so quickly.</p>
<p>Overall Chris is doing well. He feels better and stronger everyday. We are just taking life one moment at a time and enjoying each other as much as possible. I love him so much and I cannot wait for to see him healthy and happy again soon!</p>
<p>Thank you for your prayers&#8230;we truly feel the love and support from everyone. It&#8217;s very moving&#8230;and we are touched by your kindness and sincerity.</p>
<p>Love, Amy</p></div>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textNormal12"></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td height="25">
<hr size="1" /></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textTimeHeader" height="20" valign="top">WEDNESDAY, OCTOBER 08, 2008 05:39 PM, CDT</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textNormal12">
<div style="overflow: auto;">Today was very emotional and heavy. We met with our oncologist this morning and he said he met with his colleges at MD Anderson and we basically have 3 options.</p>
<p>Option one&#8230;.<br />
Wait and watch in between this chemo treatment&#8230;make sure the lump does NOT grow back &#8230;..then hit it again with HIGH DOSE chemo as well as introduce a new drug, that is successful in treating aggressive lymphomas.</p>
<p>Option two&#8230;.<br />
Go to NCI..( National Cancer Institute) receive high dose chemo (even higher than he is receiving now) and receive an AUTO stem cell transplant. This is a procedure that takes 6 weeks&#8230;they extract Chris own stem cells&#8230;.kill the cancer then immediately give the cells back to Chris. This is often times called a &#8216;rebirth&#8217;. It basically cleanses the body of all cancerous cells and provides a clean slate.</p>
<p>Option three&#8230;<br />
Go to NCI. Receive high dose chemo. Extract Chris&#8217; sister, Audrey&#8217;s Stem cells and give them back to Chris. There is a 1 in 5 chance of her being a match. There is a 10% chance Chris&#8217; body could reject her cells ( Graph versus Host disease) and it could be fatal. But the good news is that if they are a match and his body accepts Audrey&#8217;s cells&#8230;it will breathe new life into Chris&#8217; body and Audrey&#8217;s healthy stem cells with fight Chris&#8217; cancer for him. ( this is called Graph versus Tumor).</p>
<p>So&#8230;here we are&#8230;playing the waiting game again. I am hoping that this thing does not grow back and that Chris can kick it once and for all.<br />
This has been 5 long months&#8230;7 chemo treatments&#8230;and a lot of tears and frustration. I pray that one day we have our victory in all of this.</p>
<p>Chris and I want to thank you for the beautiful messages you all of have left on our guest book. They bring us/him so much hope.</p>
<p>We are truly grateful for our friends and family and the friends of family who are praying for him. Your thoughts and prayers lift him up and provided a sense of peace in the face of this challenging situation.</p>
<p>We love you guys!</p>
<p>Amy</p></div>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textNormal12"></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td height="25">
<hr size="1" /></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textTimeHeader" height="20" valign="top">TUESDAY, OCTOBER 07, 2008 10:06 AM, CDT</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textNormal12">
<div style="overflow: auto;">Chris told me last night that he felt like everything that the docs tell you &#8230;.you might experience during chemo&#8230;&#8230;he&#8217;s definitely had every symptom this time around. I feel so helpless because I can&#8217;t do anything to make him feel better. I picked up 5 prescriptions yesterday to alleviate the side effects of chemo&#8230;he&#8217;s never taken this much medicine in his life.<br />
Chris has been sleeping and resting a lot&#8230; which is the very BEST thing to do after such high doses of chemo. I have never seen him like this before. Each treatment gets worse&#8230;as far as feeling BAD goes.<br />
We are anxiously awaiting our appointment tomorrow with Dr.Sunnuberg. Can&#8217;t wait to see what he has to say and what he thinks of Chris&#8217; progress this time around. We pray that we find a solution and that he will not have to endure much more of this.<br />
He i going in for his shot today.  Maybe this will make him feel better and get his counts up.</p>
<p>Love, Amy</p></div>
<div style="overflow: auto;">
<table id="table43" style="table-layout: fixed;" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%">
<tbody>
<tr>
<td class="textTimeHeader" height="20" valign="top">MONDAY, OCTOBER 06, 2008 10:47 AM, CDT</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textNormal12">
<div style="overflow: auto;">Chris came home form the hospital around 3 pm and slept for about three hours then hung out with me for awhile then we went back to bed and slept all night. He says he feels really worn out. He is doing well aside from the soars in his mouth, but the doctor gave us this stuff called &#8216;magic mouthwash&#8217; that is supposed to help a lot.</p>
<p>Now for the exciting news&#8230;.The lump is GONE! I can not see it anymore AT ALL! The trick is for it to stay this way. Usually after chemo&#8230;I could still see and feel a residual layer under his skin that was like a flat tumor&#8230;almost &#8216;disc like&#8217;. But now it is almost concave in that area. I am so happy! I love to see him respond this way to chemo because it is really promising. We have an appointment with Dr. Sunnenberg and I can not wait for him to see this. I&#8217;m really curious what he is going to say about it all. Dr. Sunnenberg returned form MD. Anderson today and I am hoping he will have a plan for Chris that will knock him right into remission!!!!</p>
<p>Keep your fingers crossed!!!!</p>
<p>So&#8230;it&#8217;s back to work for both of us! I&#8217;m so happy we are home and that Chris is doing well. He gets his shot tomorrow to boost his blood cells and they will check his levels to make sure that he is doing alright. I will keep you all posted.</p>
<p>Love you guys!</p>
<p>Amy</p></div>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textNormal12"></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td height="25">
<hr size="1" /></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textTimeHeader" height="20" valign="top">SUNDAY, OCTOBER 05, 2008 10:07 AM, CDT</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textNormal12">
<div style="overflow: auto;">We had our favorite nurse last night. Her name is Nancy and she is AMAZING. Every nurse should take lessons from her because she truly has a passion for nursing. Nancy worked at a cancer facility in South Carolina and she worked in the lymphoma department&#8230;so, she knows SO much about what Chris is going through. She NEVER wakes him up in the middle of the night by talking his ear off at 2am ( you wouldn&#8217;t believe how many nurses do this)&#8230;she spoils him (and me) rotten with ice cream and warm blankets. She even showed up at our house last time, to check on Chris because he had such a rough morning before he was discharged. We love Nancy so much&#8230;she&#8217;s like family.</p>
<p>So, we are getting out of here today!YEA! Chris&#8217; last bag of chemo runs at 3 pm. He will be able to sleep in his own bed tonight and actually get solid sleep.<br />
He didn&#8217;t have any complications this time. Pheeew! Every time is different and we just never know what might happen. I think we have this nausea thing down pat, though. The trick is to just say your nauseous when the nurses ask&#8230; and keep the meds flowing. Better safe then sorry!</p>
<p>We are going to get through this&#8230;In fact&#8230;.we ARE getting through this! I told Chris one day we will look at each other and this will be a distant memory&#8230;and we will wonder how we got through it all&#8230;BUT we did!!!</p>
<p>We love you guys and thank you for all your support! We feel so blessed!</p>
<p>Love, Amy</p></div>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textNormal12"></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td height="25">
<hr size="1" /></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textTimeHeader" height="20" valign="top">SATURDAY, OCTOBER 04, 2008 05:34 PM, CDT</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textNormal12">
<div style="overflow: auto;">Well kids&#8230;it&#8217;s just another day in the life of me. The Methotrexate I have been given is just about out of my body as I have been drinking a ton of fluids. The toughest thing about this 5 day period is the fact I feel caged. It&#8217;s yet another layer on feeling as if my life is completely on hold. I am just ready to be in remission and enjoying every moment with my beautiful wife. I am telling you this as fact&#8230;she is my cure. Everything that has progressed in the right direction is because of her. She asks about treatment that doctors eventually come to as a solution. She connected us with a brilliant doctor and his colleagues. The tumor has reduced significantly and I think this &#8216;B&#8217; portion of the Hyper CVAD treatment is the key. The &#8216;A&#8217; did not seem to work and is along the same lines as the old RChops that were a total waste in the beginning.</p>
<p>I have always conquered and learned from my past challenges and this is no different. The one thing I can take from this at this point is that there is no greater love than I experience from Amy every day. Other than that, I don&#8217;t feel I need any other life lessons out of this. I was living it to the fullest before, appreciative of every moment, and now that has been put on hold. If anything, hopefully others can see that even in the most fearful situation we all make our decision. I have come to love this part in life. I refuse to sit on the sidelines whether the outcome good or bad. I have made my decision and that is to stomp this into remission and get back to loving my wife at the deepest level and taking life on with utter success.</p>
<p>I love you all. Have a beautiful weekend.</p>
<p>Love,<br />
Christopher</p></div>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textNormal12"></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td height="25">
<hr size="1" /></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textTimeHeader" height="20" valign="top">SATURDAY, OCTOBER 04, 2008 10:47 AM, CDT</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textNormal12">
<div style="overflow: auto;">Well&#8230;.Chris got absolutely NO sleep last night. He had a very busy day/night. He had a lumbar puncture and a blood transfusion on top of all the chemo. The nurse came in about 50 times last night. My Dad and Aunt Anna came by this morning to check on us. We visited with them for about an hour and laughed a little about my dad and his funny little words he makes up. Chris&#8217; friend from college (Eric) came by last night and talked with Chris for awhile. Today Brooke (another college friend) will be coming by to visit. She is in town from Tallahassee and is in a Triathlon today. Chris is looking forward to seeing her&#8230;she was in our wedding and it&#8217;s been a while since they have seen each other.<br />
Our oncologist is still in Houston&#8230;but his partner came by this morning and said that there is another chemo regimen that they will most likely work Chris into. It contains two other drugs that Chris has never had before on top of the ones that he responds so well to.<br />
When he woke up this morning&#8230;I noticed that the lump on the side of his face was FLAT. Completely flat!!!! Now if we can get it to stay like this!!! Hopefully these two new drugs will kick the lymphoma&#8217;s butt!!! Our doctor said that the two new ones are VERY successful in treating aggressive lymphoma. I feel like we are getting closer to our answer.<br />
Chris will get to go outside today!  His blood counts look good, he&#8217;s eating well, and looks strong!</p>
<p>We are so grateful for all the support of our friends and family! You have no idea how much you comments and phone calls mean to us and especially to Chris!</p>
<p>Love,<br />
Amy</p></div>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textNormal12"></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td height="25">
<hr size="1" /></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textTimeHeader" height="20" valign="top">FRIDAY, OCTOBER 03, 2008 11:34 AM, CDT</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="textNormal12">
<div style="overflow: auto;">We had an appointment with our oncologist Dr. Sunnenburg Wednesday morning to show him how Chris responded to his last chemo treatment. We noticed a slight change in the lump and wanted him to see it and make a judgment call on whether this line of chemo is working. Dr. Sunnenberg decided to admit Chris right away to do the portion of the chemo regimen that has been so successful the first two times. This means Chris is a week ahead of schedule. His counts looked really good and he feels strong, so Dr. Sunnenberg wanted to seize the moment and &#8216;go for it&#8217;.<br />
The GREAT news is that Dr. Sunnenberg has an appointment at MD Anderson in Houston to meet with a LYMPHOMA specialist on Friday ( today). He will present Chris&#8217; case to this doctor in hopes of finding the perfect chemo regime&#8217;s to put him in remission!!!<br />
Now&#8230;being the computer savvy person that Chris is &#8230;he presented Dr. Sunneberg with a power point presentation of the pictures we have taken on this journey of Chris and his response to each treatment. We have documented everything!!!! Dr Sunnenberg was thrilled and is sending it to Emory University to our oncologist there as well as showing it at MD Anderson. We ask that everyone keep Chris in your thoughts. We are asking that the RIGHT answers come forth to get Chris into remission!!!<br />
Chris looks good&#8230;he feels good. This chemo kicks his butt for a few days after he returns home but then he is fine and back to normal ( well, as normal as you can be after getting tons of chemo dumped into your body)</p>
<p>Chris and I are so grateful for our friends and family for lifting us up in this situation.</p>
<p>Love,<br />
Amy</p></div>
</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
		</div><!-- end .entry -->
	</div><!-- end .post -->

	
	
